Running a business as a self-employed, introverted creative who values their private life shouldn't be complicated, yet it often is. Most online resources and coaches tell you to work with big (and diabolical) tech companies using extroverted techniques. Do advertising here, follow the algorithm, share who you are. Have your service verified, be available 24/7, respond to questions with a video of yourself, respond right away. Video, video, video.
January 3, 2024
It's a transitional year for me.
I don't want to fuel the big tech companies with my money, my data, and my energy. Nor do I want coaches who have a one-size-fits-all approach that they apply to everyone. I'm exploring new ways to manage my activities while fighting the idea I've long believed: that you have to do things a certain way to be successful.
Wish me good luck!
I've already taken the first steps.
I left FB, removed all Meta and Pinterest trackers from my website, and deleted my private WhatsApp account.
I also removed the last external tracker, Google Analytics, from my website yesterday and it feels good.
I recently subscribed to a European-based CRM for better RGPD compliance, and I will be transferring my activity over the coming weeks.
I've transferred my MX to Proton and I'm now fully taking advantage of SPF, DKIM, and DMARC without having to pay Google for basic email address validation.
